WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.380
Good afternoon, everyone. Thank you so much for coming to our mini symposium this

2
00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:13.360
afternoon on the novel molecular mechanisms driving cancer

3
00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:16.820
metastasis. I'd like to first acknowledge

4
00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:21.340
the reviewers who helped us choose which talks are going to be part of this

5
00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:25.270
mini symposium. So all of the reviewers, we had about five or six reviewers,

6
00:00:25.300 --> 00:00:29.220
who contributed and voted on which talks would be selected for the mini symposium.

7
00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:34.240
So to start off, they asked us to do a very brief introduction.

8
00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:38.800
So I wanted to very briefly introduce some of the basic concepts of

9
00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:41.780
metastasis that many of our talks will be focused on.

10
00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:46.500
So as we know, cancer metastasis is a multi-step process,

11
00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:51.020
where these primary solid tumors will have

12
00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:55.000
cells and metastasis-initiating cells that were able to

13
00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:58.720
escape this primary tumor through a process of invasive migration.

14
00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:03.510
And they will enter into the circulation at one point, either through

15
00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:06.300
the lymphatics or the blood circulation.

16
00:01:06.340 --> 00:01:10.300
And then these circulating tumor cells will circle around the circulation

17
00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:14.280
and eventually be able to extravasate out of the

18
00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:14.680
vessel

19
00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:19.480
until they get into a secondary organ, where they can start

20
00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:23.040
to form these micrometastases during the process of

21
00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:24.520
metastatic colonization.

22
00:01:25.380 --> 00:01:29.200
So there's a lot of different components to this process, and we will hear about

23
00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:32.320
different aspects of this process through several of the talks today.

24
00:01:33.240 --> 00:01:36.780
In particular, I want to come back to this invasive migration part,

25
00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:41.100
and the tumor cell interaction with the extracellular matrix is a big

26
00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:45.090
component of this process. We will hear several talks today talking about

27
00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:48.200
the tumor cell interaction with the ECM.

28
00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:48.780
In addition,

29
00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:53.520
during metastasis, tumor cells also have to be able to evade

30
00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:57.760
the immune system and immune detection in order to successfully complete this

31
00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:01.720
process. And we know that metastatic tumors at the end of this

32
00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:05.460
process do have a different interaction with immune

33
00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:09.280
cells in that they are typically a bit more immune suppressed than

34
00:02:09.361 --> 00:02:10.320
primary tumors.

35
00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:14.510
And then lastly, I'll introduce as well this concept of the

36
00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:18.220
plasticity that is involved in metastasis, in that

37
00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:22.040
cells are able to use their plastic nature

38
00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:26.080
to accomplish several of these different steps of the metastatic

39
00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:29.960
process. So we will hear a little bit about this as well, and that

40
00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:33.960
goes for everything from tumor-initiating cancer stem cells, to things like

41
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:35.799
epithelial-mesenchymal transition.

42
00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:40.200
All of these things that give these cells this plastic nature do

43
00:02:40.260 --> 00:02:43.200
ultimately, we know, help this metastatic process.

44
00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:48.310
So here is our lineup of talks, and we can actually have our first

45
00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:52.290
speaker come on up. And we will go through

46
00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:56.010
these talks, and at the end of this, we will have about five to 10 minutes

47
00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:58.100
left for an open discussion

48
00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:02.940
about the topics that are covered here today and the process of metastasis.

49
00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:07.340
So we'd like to welcome our first speaker up, if they are here. Yeah.

50
00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:18.920
Okay.

51
00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:23.300
Hello, everyone. My name is Alaleh.

52
00:03:23.460 --> 00:03:26.140
I'm a PhD candidate from University of Florida,

53
00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:30.600
Biomedical Sciences, and I'm so happy here,

54
00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:33.300
especially Mr. Jim, my sponsor.

55
00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:37.920
So today I want to talk about senescence cancer cells,

56
00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:41.840
which often known as static

57
00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:42.860
and

58
00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:46.720
secretory cells in the tumor microenvironment.

59
00:03:46.780 --> 00:03:48.400
But here today, I want to

60
00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:53.650
show that they're also actively involved in

61
00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:56.860
metastasis through clustering and immune modulation.

62
00:03:58.480 --> 00:03:59.440
So my disclosure.

63
00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:04.300
In response to different type of cancer therapies like chemotherapy and

64
00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:06.680
irradiation, cells can have different fates.

65
00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:10.970
Bulk of the cells will die, some cells can survive, and there are a

66
00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:12.520
subset of cells that can

67
00:04:13.900 --> 00:04:17.709
permanently stop from proliferating, known as senescence or

68
00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:21.721
therapy-induced senescence. These cells were initially known to be

69
00:04:21.780 --> 00:04:25.420
beneficial to the tumor microenvironment, since they can cease the

70
00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:29.200
proliferation and also through secreting inflammatory

71
00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:32.980
factors known as senescence-associated secretory phenotype,

72
00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:37.400
or SASP, which is including chemokines, cytokines, growth

73
00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:40.780
factors, and this can promote immune surveillance.

74
00:04:41.360 --> 00:04:45.180
But later, scientists also find out that these cells can be involved in

75
00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:49.040
tumorigenesis, metastasis, and relapse through the same

76
00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:52.940
SASP, but over time. So given this opposing

77
00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:56.400
effect, we became interested to look at senescent cells in

78
00:04:56.460 --> 00:05:00.240
cancer. First, we wanted to confirm that therapy can

79
00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:04.200
induce these therapy-induced senescence cells in vivo.

80
00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.500
So if you look here, this is the X-gal staining or senescence

81
00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:11.460
staining from immunodeficient NSG mice

82
00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:15.240
tumor tissues bearing human triple negative breast

83
00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:19.200
cancer 231 treated with chemotherapy doxorubicin

84
00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:22.500
from lower doses to higher doses after seven days.

85
00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:26.460
And in blue color, you can see that there is a significant dose-dependent

86
00:05:26.500 --> 00:05:27.590
senescence induction.

87
00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:32.420
Also, when we looked at BALB/c immunocompetent mice bearing

88
00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:35.840
more triple negative breast cancer cell lines, following by

89
00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:40.940
fractionated irradiation after seven days, we could see that there is a robust

90
00:05:40.950 --> 00:05:42.080
senescence induction.

91
00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:46.480
So different cancer therapies could induce senescence in different

92
00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:49.560
cancer types and in different animal

93
00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:53.308
models.Then we establish an in vitro model for our

94
00:05:53.868 --> 00:05:57.368
subsequent experiment. And for that, we treated 231 cells

95
00:05:57.728 --> 00:06:01.228
with doxorubicin from lower doses to higher doses

96
00:06:02.528 --> 00:06:06.288
based on IC50. And then in H&amp;E staining after seven

97
00:06:06.368 --> 00:06:10.208
days, in green color, you can see that there is a dose-dependent senescence

98
00:06:10.228 --> 00:06:13.408
induction, although many cells died at higher

99
00:06:13.428 --> 00:06:17.298
doses. Then we confirmed the senescence induction by looking at

100
00:06:17.328 --> 00:06:21.078
the mRNA levels of beta-galactosidase and

101
00:06:21.148 --> 00:06:24.228
also some of the SASP factors like p16,

102
00:06:24.328 --> 00:06:28.128
p21, and MMP3. And then we observed

103
00:06:28.188 --> 00:06:31.728
that in 39 nanomolar doxorubicin, after seven days, we have

104
00:06:31.818 --> 00:06:34.708
maximal senescence induction and minimal cell death.

105
00:06:35.248 --> 00:06:37.228
So after confirming this condition

106
00:06:39.188 --> 00:06:42.788
by beta-galactosidase probes, we used this condition for our

107
00:06:42.848 --> 00:06:44.008
subsequent experiment.

108
00:06:45.048 --> 00:06:48.848
The first question was how this TERP-induced senescence can affect tumor

109
00:06:48.868 --> 00:06:52.588
progression. So for that, we injected 231 parental

110
00:06:52.628 --> 00:06:56.108
cells and also co-injection of these cells with senescent

111
00:06:56.148 --> 00:06:58.718
cells orthotopically to the NSG mice.

112
00:06:58.768 --> 00:07:02.388
And then we evaluated tumor sizes, and at the end, we looked at lung

113
00:07:02.408 --> 00:07:05.268
metastasis. That was really interesting to see.

114
00:07:05.368 --> 00:07:09.248
In the presence of senescent cells, there is no effect on primary

115
00:07:09.268 --> 00:07:11.788
tumor growth in compare with parental injection.

116
00:07:12.568 --> 00:07:15.888
But then when we looked at the lung metastasis, we could see that

117
00:07:17.388 --> 00:07:21.208
metastatic increased significantly in the co-injection in

118
00:07:21.268 --> 00:07:22.878
compare with parental cells alone.

119
00:07:23.268 --> 00:07:26.688
So this led us to this question, how these TERP-induced senescent cells can

120
00:07:26.748 --> 00:07:30.708
increase metastasis without having any effect on primary tumor growth.

121
00:07:31.648 --> 00:07:35.048
Then we decided to focus on other steps of metastatic

122
00:07:35.108 --> 00:07:38.928
cascade, because we didn't see any effect on primary tumor, by doing

123
00:07:38.988 --> 00:07:42.828
tail vein injection. In this experiment, we used 231

124
00:07:42.868 --> 00:07:46.728
parental cells expressing luciferase and then co-injection of

125
00:07:46.748 --> 00:07:50.508
these cells with unlabeled senescent cells to the NSG mice.

126
00:07:50.558 --> 00:07:52.188
And then we did in vivo imaging.

127
00:07:53.548 --> 00:07:57.388
What we observe, after just three days, we could see that there

128
00:07:57.428 --> 00:08:01.368
is an increase in early dissemination of parental cells into

129
00:08:01.408 --> 00:08:05.208
the lung when we co-injected with senescent cells in compare with

130
00:08:05.228 --> 00:08:08.568
parental. It means that senescent cells can act early in the

131
00:08:08.608 --> 00:08:12.188
metastatic cascade. We wanted to look more

132
00:08:12.228 --> 00:08:15.848
closely to this early dissemination, so we did another set of

133
00:08:16.148 --> 00:08:19.608
tail vein injection. This time, our parental cells expressed

134
00:08:19.668 --> 00:08:22.588
GFV and senescent cells expressed tdTomato.

135
00:08:22.998 --> 00:08:26.888
And then following lung clearing, we did 3D imaging after

136
00:08:27.128 --> 00:08:27.808
72 hours.

137
00:08:28.948 --> 00:08:32.889
3D images shows that in the presence of senescent cells, not only

138
00:08:32.968 --> 00:08:36.928
parental cells could disseminate more into the lung in compare

139
00:08:36.989 --> 00:08:40.338
with parental, but also these disseminated cells were in

140
00:08:40.509 --> 00:08:43.889
larger clusters in compare with parental injection.

141
00:08:45.308 --> 00:08:49.228
Also, in the high-resolution images of this lung, surprisingly,

142
00:08:49.268 --> 00:08:52.588
we could see that senescent cells in white could also

143
00:08:52.598 --> 00:08:56.528
extravasate to the lung tissue, which as I mentioned before, they're known

144
00:08:56.568 --> 00:08:59.168
to be static in the tumor microenvironment.

145
00:08:59.228 --> 00:09:03.188
And also in the presence of these senescent cells, GFV expressed parental

146
00:09:03.248 --> 00:09:07.228
cells could extravasate more efficiently

147
00:09:07.268 --> 00:09:10.908
and in larger clusters in compare with parental

148
00:09:11.008 --> 00:09:13.788
injection alone, which seems dispersed and scatter.

149
00:09:14.608 --> 00:09:17.708
So this led us to investigate underlying mechanism.

150
00:09:18.077 --> 00:09:21.448
And RNA sequencing showed that there is a significant

151
00:09:21.548 --> 00:09:25.028
enrichment of adhesion-related pathways in

152
00:09:25.068 --> 00:09:27.428
senescence in compare with parental cells.

153
00:09:27.808 --> 00:09:31.188
It means that senescent cells may have an increase in their cell-cell

154
00:09:31.228 --> 00:09:33.408
interaction and adhesion capacity.

155
00:09:34.288 --> 00:09:38.008
But to test this adhesion and cell-cell interaction, we performed

156
00:09:38.828 --> 00:09:42.568
adhesion assay. And for that, we added tdTomato expressed

157
00:09:42.608 --> 00:09:46.528
parental cells on top of the attached unlabeled senescent

158
00:09:46.568 --> 00:09:49.108
cells, parental cells, and Matrigel.

159
00:09:49.168 --> 00:09:53.028
And then immediately after wash, we counted remaining cells, and

160
00:09:53.088 --> 00:09:56.838
we found out that parental cells tend to attach more

161
00:09:56.888 --> 00:10:00.368
strongly and in significantly higher numbers to

162
00:10:00.388 --> 00:10:02.648
senescent cells in compare with other groups.

163
00:10:03.508 --> 00:10:07.488
When we looked at this result more closely, we could see that each

164
00:10:07.608 --> 00:10:11.248
senescent cell in gray here could bind

165
00:10:11.348 --> 00:10:15.328
to multiple tumor cells at the same time in red

166
00:10:16.248 --> 00:10:20.188
spontaneously. It means that senescent cells create this hub to

167
00:10:20.288 --> 00:10:21.548
bring cells together.

168
00:10:22.628 --> 00:10:26.088
And consistent with this result, we found out that in the presence of

169
00:10:26.108 --> 00:10:29.968
senescent cells, we could see that there is a significant cluster

170
00:10:30.008 --> 00:10:33.908
formation in compare with parental cells culture alone.

171
00:10:34.548 --> 00:10:38.398
It means that senescent cells increase the cluster formation through

172
00:10:38.568 --> 00:10:39.268
adhesion.

173
00:10:41.228 --> 00:10:44.408
So then we got interested on adhesion molecules.

174
00:10:44.448 --> 00:10:47.778
When we look at the adhesion molecules from our RNA sequencing

175
00:10:47.848 --> 00:10:51.778
result from co-culture in compare with parental, we got

176
00:10:51.848 --> 00:10:55.588
interested on JUP specifically, since it's already known to be

177
00:10:56.388 --> 00:10:58.088
involved in CTC clustering.

178
00:10:59.088 --> 00:11:02.918
JUP or plakoglobin here is one of the key component of

179
00:11:02.948 --> 00:11:06.188
desmosomal protein, which links adhesion to

180
00:11:06.288 --> 00:11:07.348
cytoskeleton.

181
00:11:08.648 --> 00:11:12.048
That was really surprising when we see that when we knock out

182
00:11:12.168 --> 00:11:16.138
JUP, senescent cells significantly lost their adhesion and

183
00:11:16.248 --> 00:11:20.048
cell-cell interaction in compare with wild type senescent cells.

184
00:11:21.368 --> 00:11:24.998
And also in the presence of senescent cells in co-culture with

185
00:11:25.088 --> 00:11:28.428
parental cells, cluster formation significantly

186
00:11:28.488 --> 00:11:31.628
disrupted in compare with wild type co-culture.

187
00:11:32.968 --> 00:11:36.788
Importantly, when we co-injected senesence JUP knockout

188
00:11:36.868 --> 00:11:40.308
cells with parental cells, we could see that early

189
00:11:40.328 --> 00:11:43.888
dissemination of parental cells significantly reduced in

190
00:11:43.988 --> 00:11:46.128
compare with wild type co-injection.

191
00:11:46.528 --> 00:11:50.448
It means that expression of JUP in senescent cells is

192
00:11:50.508 --> 00:11:54.448
required for parental cells dissemination and metastatic

193
00:11:54.458 --> 00:11:58.232
to the lung.But then we asked this question whether immune

194
00:11:58.312 --> 00:12:00.292
system is involved in this phenomenon.

195
00:12:01.492 --> 00:12:05.352
So for that, we established another in vitro model, and

196
00:12:05.472 --> 00:12:09.032
we irradiated 41 from lower doses to higher doses of

197
00:12:09.052 --> 00:12:12.992
irradiation, and we could see that there is a significant dose dependence

198
00:12:13.012 --> 00:12:16.592
in senescence induction, which were confirmed in the mRNA levels of

199
00:12:16.632 --> 00:12:20.492
p21 and interleukin 6. Then we confirmed

200
00:12:20.532 --> 00:12:23.992
this result, and we used this condition for subsequent experiment.

201
00:12:24.452 --> 00:12:28.272
In the co-injection of these cells in NSG immunodeficient mice, we could

202
00:12:28.372 --> 00:12:31.872
see that there is a significant early dissemination of the cells,

203
00:12:32.252 --> 00:12:35.812
but then metastatic growth and enhancement was limited,

204
00:12:36.052 --> 00:12:39.992
same as 231 model. But when we did the same experiment in

205
00:12:40.112 --> 00:12:43.772
BALB/c immunocompetent mice, we could see that not only early

206
00:12:43.792 --> 00:12:47.612
dissemination of the cells increased, but also metastatic

207
00:12:47.712 --> 00:12:51.332
outgrowth over time continued, even more than seven

208
00:12:51.412 --> 00:12:55.072
days. So it means that other than clustering, immune modulation

209
00:12:55.132 --> 00:12:58.532
is also involved in the presence of senescent cells.

210
00:12:58.572 --> 00:13:02.432
So in overall, therapies can induce senescence in subset of cells, and

211
00:13:02.472 --> 00:13:06.022
these cells increase metastatic through two step mechanism.

212
00:13:06.552 --> 00:13:10.052
First, by creating clusters through JUP dependent

213
00:13:10.132 --> 00:13:13.652
adhesion and increase early dissemination of the cells, and then

214
00:13:13.692 --> 00:13:17.552
by promoting metastatic outgrowth through immune modulation.

215
00:13:17.612 --> 00:13:20.132
With that, thank you, and I'm happy to take any question.

216
00:13:26.152 --> 00:13:27.212
We have five minutes for

217
00:13:29.152 --> 00:13:30.092
questions if you'd like to ask.

218
00:13:32.332 --> 00:13:35.712
Hi, I have a quick question. Did you test your

